extends layout

block content
  // container Div
  .container.font-weight-bold.lead
    .d-flex.justify-content-between.flex-wrap.mt-5
      // gallery Div
      .bookDetails.d-flex.flex-no-wrap
        // book Div
        .bookDiv
          img.card-img-top(src=`${itemImg}`, alt=`${itemTitle}`)
          if related.length
            .card.mt-5
              .card-header
                | You May Also Like:
              ul.list-group.list-group-flush
                each relate in related
                  li.list-group-item #{relate.Name}

        .card-body
          p #{itemTitle}
          p #{itemAuthor}
          p #{itemGenre} | #{itemYear}
          p.description
            | #{itemDescription}
          hr
          p.lead Reviews
          .d-flex.justify-content-between.flex-wrap
            // gallery Div
            .reviewlist.d-flex.flex-no-wrap.mb-2
              // book Div
              .reviewDiv
                img.card-img-top.rounded-circle(src='static/images/jasper_babe.jpg', alt='Book Title')
              .card-body
                p Chelsea rated it 5 stars
                p Date
                p.review
                  | In 2000, Jhumpa Lahiri won the Pulitzer Prize for her story collection Interpreter of Maladies, becoming the first Indian to win the award. In the last story, an engineering graduate student arrives in Cambridge from Calcutta, starting a life in a new country. This story is the basis for The Namesake, Lahiri's first full length novel where she weaves together elements from her own life to paint a picture of the Indian immigrant experience in the United States.
